A farmer field school is a school without walls. A group of farmers gets together in one of their own fields to learn about their crops and things that affect them. They learn how to farm better by observing, analysing and trying out new ideas on their own fields. \n\nFAO and other development organizations have been promoting farmer field schools \u2013 an innovative approach to adult education first developed in Southeast Asia for pest management \u2013 to improve land and water management in Africa. Unlike traditional approaches to agricultural extension, which rely on extension workers providing advice to farmers, farmer field schools enable groups of farmers to find out the answers for themselves. That means the farmers can develop solutions to their own problems.

Increase rice yields by allowing rice plants to tolerate flooding. Farmers maintain rice yields even in years with persistent flooding (South Asia and SSA). w/BMGF via IRRI Submergence-tolerant varieties reached 1.2 M farmers by 2011. 120 M small rice farmers stand to benefit worldwide, but primarily South Asia (Bangladesh,
India, Burma, and Pakistan).

IRRI, in the relevant section of the Promising CGIAR Technologies Report notes: Submergence tolerance. The QTL SUB1 has been identified on chromosome 9 and introgressed into various mega-varieties through MAS. This QTL is able to confer tolerance of submergence for 2 weeks. Work is being done at IRRI to extend the tolerance to more than 2 weeks.
Different levels of characterization are useful for different purposes, and it would be helpful to develop a common vocabulary appropriate for the purpose. "Submergence tolerant rice" is too broad for meaningful consideration of potential scaling, and "QTL SUB1" is probably too narrow for most audiences.
